The paper proposes a method for efficient visual landmark localization, which is a task related to computer vision. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of memory-efficient implementation and quantization of weights, inputs, and gradients, which are related to machine learning and optimization, suggesting that cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) are also likely sub-categories. Additionally, the paper proposes an iterative refinement technique, which involves updating the model iteratively, indicating that cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper validates the proposed approach in two tasks: human pose estimation and face alignment, which are related to multimedia and image processing, suggesting that cs.MM (Multimedia) is also a possible sub-category.
